# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arthur-compton
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The **1901 Nobel Prize in Physics** was presented in a ceremony in Stockholm, Sweden to the German Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen, "in recognition of the extraordinary services he has rendered by the discovery of the remarkable rays subsequently named after him", namely, X-rays.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] It was the first of its kind resulting from the will of the Swedish chemist Alfred Nobel in 1895 to recognize "the person who made the most important discovery or invention in the field of physics".
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Wilhelm Röntgen (1845–1923) was a German physicist at the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München (LMU) and a member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences when he received the Nobel Prize.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Whilst he was at the University of Würzburg and experimenting with cathode ray tubes, Röntgen discovered on 8 November 1895 that some waves could penetrate objects and record their transparent likenesses on photographic plates.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Röntgen announced his discoveries, which he named X-rays, in a brief note to the Physico-medical Society of Würzburg entitled *Eine neue Art von Strahlen* ("On a New Kind of Rays").
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] It immediately attracted enormous popular and scientific attention worldwide, with over one thousand books, pamphlets and articles appearing on the phenomenon, which Rudolph Albert von Kölliker dubbed "Röntgen rays", in just the year 1896.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Deliberately left unpatented by Röntgen, by 1901, X-rays were seeing widespread use in hospitals, inspired further research into radiation, including among many future Nobel laureates, and made its discoverer into a celebrity.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] For instance, in 1900 alone, Röntgen received the Barnard Medal from Columbia University, and was made Knight of the Order of Merit of the Bavarian Crown and Prussian Order of the Crown 2nd Class.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] X-rays are still known in some languages as Röntgen rays, and images produced with them as roentgenograms.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The Nobel Prize in Physics is awarded by an absolute majority vote of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences from among the persons given valid nominations by scientists and/or Academy members qualified to do so.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The Academy held a plenary session on 12 November, with the secretary being Swedish chemist Wilhelm Palmær.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] There is no record of either proceedings or individual votes to comply with standards on secrecy.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Within the Academy, there is a specialist Nobel Committee for Physics, usually composed of Swedes, who issue their own proposals and judgement.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Röntgen was nominated by sixteen of the 29 nominators.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Members of the Academy are denoted with an asterisk (*) in the table below.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The five members of the Committee all divided their nominations between Röntgen and fellow German Philipp Lenard, who received the second-most number of nominations, i.e., six.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Members of that Committee are denoted with a dagger (†).
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Nominations must have been received before 1 February 1901.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] As was the case until 1910, the identity of the winners was not revealed until the prize ceremony the following month.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Note that two of the nominees died between 1 February and the plenary session: Henry Augustus Rowland, on 16 April 1901, and Adolf Erik Nordenskiöld, on 12 August; therefore, they would be disqualified for a Nobel Prize, whose recipient must be living.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Additionally, at least two nominations (including Rowland's) were disallowed because they were self-nominations.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The Nobel Prize ceremonies began at 7 p.m. on Tuesday, 10 December 1901, the fifth anniversary of Nobel's death.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] As until 1926, the scientific Prizes were presented in the hall of the Royal Swedish Academy of Music in Nybroviken, Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The presentation speeches for the Prizes in Physics and Chemistry were delivered by Clas Theodor Odhner, President of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, and former Rector of the National Archives of Sweden.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Röntgen was then presented with the Nobel diploma (designed by Sofia Gisberg) and medal from Crown Prince Gustaf, the future Gustaf V, in the King's absence.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] After the other medals were awarded, the laureates attended a banquet, held as until 1930 in the Grand Hôtel, Stockholm.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Unlike the other laureates, Röntgen did not deliver a lecture the following day and left instead.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] In fact, he was intensely shy, refused interviews and resented publicity.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] In accordance with Nobel's will, the prize money was divided to the laureates from the income of safe investments made by the Nobel Foundation from his vast fortune.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Accounting for inflation, this would be the most paid to a Nobel laureate until 1991.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] It is sometimes said that Röntgen donated this prize to the University of Würzburg after his death—while he did dedicate nearly that amount in his testament of 1920 (200,000 M), it was never specifically linked to the Nobel Prize.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] In any case, the hyperinflation of the German Mark contemporary with Röntgen's death in 1923 essentially made his bequest worthless.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Despite the renown of Röntgen's invention, papers in the United States and the United Kingdom reported only cursorily on his receiving the Nobel Prize.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] Swedish press reports were more extensive.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] A number reprinted the faces and biographies of Röntgen and the other laureates.
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The *Stockholms Dagblad* commented on the laureates' "characteristic physiognomies", including Röntgen's "sharply defined face, projecting Teutonic strength with his long, bushy beard" (*skarpt skurna ansigte, verkande med teutonens kraft i det långa, yfviga skägget*).
[src:arthur-compton/1901-nobel-prize-in-physics] The Motala *Tidning* commented that by the discovery of X-rays, Röntgen had earned "one of the foremost places of honour in the scientific world" (*en af de främsta hedersplatserna inom den vetenskapliga världen*).
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Bergson was educated at the Lycée Condorcet and at the École Normale Supérieure, where he studied philosophy.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] He developed his philosophy through a series of publications that were well known for their original perspectives on life as well as their effective application of metaphor, imagery, and analogy.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] The notion of time that Bergson had previously proposed in his prior writings was expanded upon and used to investigate living things in *L'Évolution Créatrice* ("Creative Evolution", 1907).
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] His other principal works include *Matière et Mémoire* ("Matter and Memory", 1896), *Le Rire.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Essai sur la Signification du Comique* ("Laughter: An Essay on the Meaning of the Comic", 1900) and *Les Deux Sources de la Morale et de la Religion* ("The Two Sources of Morality and Religion", 1932).
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Bergson was not nominated in 1927 but in 1928 was awarded for this year.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] He received a total of ten nominations beginning in 1912 made Scottish author Andrew Lang.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] In 1928, he received three separate recommendations from members of the French Academy, members of the Academy of Political and Moral Sciences and professors of history of philosophy.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] In total, the Nobel Committee received 29 nominations in 1927 for authors such as Kostis Palamas, Hugo von Hofmannsthal, Thomas Hardy, Guglielmo Ferrero, Rudolf Maria Holzapfel, Olav Duun, Ada Negri and Johannes V.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] There were six authors newly nominated namely Cesare Pascarella, Eduard Meyer, Samuel Parsons Scott, Edith Wharton, Édouard Estaunié and Erwin Guido Kolbenheyer.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Of the 21 nominees, four were women: Ada Negri, Edith Wharton, Concha Espina de la Serna and Grazia Deledda (awarded for 1926).
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] The authors Ryūnosuke Akutagawa, Bernhard Alexander, Mikhail Artsybashev, Hugo Ball, Kazimir Barantsevich, Margret Holmes Bates, Martin Stanislaus Brennan, Clara Louise Burnham, John Bagnell Bury, Mabel Collins, Roi Cooper Megrue, James Oliver Curwood, Minnie S.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Davis, Robert de Flers, Federico De Roberto, Manuel Díaz Rodríguez, Osório Duque-Estrada, Georges Eekhoud, Adolfo León Gómez, Ricardo Güiraldes, Lesbia Harford, Hubert Harrison, Fukuda Hideko, Jerome K.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Jerome, Kang Youwei, Gaston Leroux, Agnes Maule Machar, Harriet Earhart Monroe, Süleyman Nazif, Jessie Penn-Lewis, Stanisław Przybyszewski, Fyodor Sologub, Borisav Stanković, Stephan G.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Stephansson, Mary Webb, Philip Wicksteed died in 1927 without having been nominated for the prize.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] During the deliberations for the 1927 prize, the Nobel committee considered the Greek poet Kostis Palamas, but his candidacy was hindered as the committee members were not able to read his poetry in the original language.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Hugo von Hofmannsthal were also considered, but the committee found his works too uneven to find support for a recommendation.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] The committee found recent works by Danish author Johannes V.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Jensen to be "overwhelmingly attractive", but the committee had "not found their merits to outweigh the offensive and hurtful features of his earlier production, otherwise remarkable for its imaginative power and immediacy.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Should the continued development correspond to the promises that have been made recently, the Committers would be happy to change their position hitherto taken." Johannes V.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Jensen was subsequently awarded the 1944 Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] On 13 November 1928, the Swedish Academy decided that the Nobel Prize for 1927 should be awarded to Henri Bergson "in recognition of his rich and vitalizing ideas and the brilliant skill with which they have been presented", and Sigrid Undset the prize for 1928.
[src:arthur-compton/1927-nobel-prize-in-literature] Bergson's candidacy had previously, and also in 1928, been dismissed as the committee found it difficult to properly evaluate his work in a field of literature where few other writers were nominated, and their reluctance to recommend non-fiction writers.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The **509th Composite Group** (**509 CG**) was a unit of the United States Army Air Forces created during World War II and tasked with the operational deployment of nuclear weapons.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It conducted the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, Japan, in August 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The group was activated on 17 December 1944 at Wendover Army Air Field, Utah.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It was commanded by Lieutenant Colonel Paul W.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Because it contained flying squadrons equipped with Boeing B-29 Superfortress bombers, C-47 Skytrain, and C-54 Skymaster transport aircraft, the group was designated as a "composite", rather than a "bombardment" formation.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It operated Silverplate B-29s, which were specially configured to enable them to carry nuclear weapons.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 509th Composite Group began deploying to North Field on Tinian, Northern Mariana Islands, in May 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] In addition to the two nuclear bombing raids, it carried out 15 practice missions against Japanese-held islands, and 12 combat missions against targets in Japan dropping high-explosive pumpkin bombs.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] In the postwar era, the 509th Composite Group was one of the original ten bombardment groups assigned to Strategic Air Command on 21 March 1946 and the only one equipped with *Silverplate* B-29 Superfortress aircraft capable of delivering atomic bombs.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It was standardized as a bombardment group and redesignated the 509th Bombardment Group, Very Heavy, on 10 July 1946.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 509th Composite Group was constituted on 9 December 1944, and activated on 17 December 1944, at Wendover Army Air Field, Utah.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Tibbets, who received promotion to full colonel in January 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It was initially assumed that the group would divide in two, with half going to Europe and half to the Pacific.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] In the first week of September Tibbets was assigned to organize a combat group to develop the means of delivering an atomic weapon by airplane against targets in Germany and Japan, then command it in combat.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Because the organization developed by Tibbets was self-sustained, with flying squadrons of both Boeing B-29 Superfortress bombers and transport aircraft, the group was designated as a "composite" rather than a "bombardment" unit.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] On 8 September, working with Major General Leslie R.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Groves, Jr.'s Manhattan Project, Tibbets selected Wendover for his training base over Great Bend Army Air Field, Kansas, and Mountain Home Army Airfield, Idaho, because of its remoteness.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] On 14 September 1944, the 393d Bombardment Squadron arrived at Wendover from its former base at Fairmont Army Air Base, Nebraska, where it had been in operational training (OTU) with the 504th Bombardment Group since 12 March.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] When its parent group deployed to the Marianas in early November 1944, the squadron was assigned directly to the Second Air Force until creation of the 509th Composite Group.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Originally consisting of twenty-one crews, fifteen were selected to continue training, and were organized into three flights of five crews, lettered A, B, and C.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 393d Bombardment Squadron was commanded by Lieutenant Colonel Thomas J.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Classen, who like Tibbets had combat experience in heavy bombers, commanding a Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress with the 11th Bombardment Group.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 393d Bombardment Squadron conducted ground school training only until delivery of three modified *Silverplate* airplanes in mid-October 1944 allowed resumption of flight training.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] These aircraft had extensive bomb bay modifications and a "weaponeer" station installed.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Initial training operations identified numerous other modifications necessary to the mission, particularly in reducing the overall weight of the airplane to offset the heavy loads it would be required to carry.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Five more *Silverplate*s were delivered in November and six in December, giving the group 14 for its training operations.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] In January and February 1945, 10 of the 15 crews under the command of the Group S-3 (operations officer) were assigned temporary duty at Batista Field, San Antonio de los Baños, Cuba, where they trained in long-range over-water navigation.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 320th Troop Carrier Squadron, the other flying unit of the 509th, came into being because of the highly secret work of the group.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The organization that was to become the 509th required its own transports for the movement of both personnel and materiel, resulting in creation of an ad hoc unit nicknamed "The Green Hornet Line".
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Crews for this unit were acquired from the five 393d crews not selected to continue B-29 training.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] All those qualified for positions with the 320th chose to remain with the 509th rather than be assigned to a replacement pool of the Second Air Force.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] They began using C-46 Commando and C-47 Skytrains already at Wendover, and in November 1944 acquired three C-54 Skymasters.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 320th Troop Carrier Squadron originally consisted of three C-54 and four C-47 aircraft.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] In April 1945 the C-47s were transferred to the 216th Army Air Forces Base Unit and two additional C-54s acquired.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 320th Troop Carrier Squadron was constituted and activated on the same dates as the group.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Other support units were activated at Wendover from personnel already present and working with Project Alberta or in the 216th Army Air Forces Base Unit, both affiliated with the Manhattan project.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Project Alberta was the part of the Manhattan Project at Site Y in Los Alamos, New Mexico, responsible for the preparation and delivery of the nuclear weapons.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Parsons, who would accompany the Hiroshima mission as weaponeer.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] On 6 March 1945, concurrent with the activation of Project Alberta, the 1st Ordnance Squadron, Special (Aviation) was activated at Wendover, again using Army Air Forces personnel on hand or already at Los Alamos.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Its purpose was to provide "skilled machinists, welders and munitions workers" and special equipment to the group to enable it to assemble atomic weapons at its operating base, thereby allowing the weapons to be transported more safely in their component parts.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] A rigorous candidate selection process was used to recruit personnel, reportedly with an 80% "washout" rate.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Not until May 1945 did the 509th Composite Group reach full strength.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 603rd Air Engineering Squadron was unique in that it provided depot-level B-29 maintenance in the field, obviating the necessity of sending aircraft back to the United States for major repairs.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] On Tinian the 603rd Air Engineering Squadron was assigned to the 313th Bombardment Wing's "C" and "D" Service Centers, where it performed provided depot-level ("third echelon") maintenance for the entire 313th Bombardment Wing when it was not engaged in 509th activities.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] With the addition of the 1st Ordnance Squadron to its roster, the 509th Composite Group had an authorized strength of 225 officers and 1,542 enlisted men, almost all of whom deployed to Tinian.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 320th Troop Carrier Squadron kept its base of operations at Wendover.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] In addition to its authorized strength, the 509th had attached to it on Tinian 51 civilian and military personnel of Project Alberta, and two representatives from Washington, D.C., the deputy director of the Manhattan Project, Brigadier General Thomas Farrell, and Rear Admiral William R.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Purnell of the Military Policy Committee.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 509th's personnel and equipment were subject to a high level of security.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] En route to Tinian on 4 June 1945, the B-29 that became *The Great Artiste* made an intermediate stop at Mather Field, near Sacramento, California.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The commanding general of the base allegedly attempted to enter the aircraft to inspect it and was warned by a plane guard who aimed his carbine at the general's chest that he could not do so.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] A similar incident occurred to a Project Alberta courier, 2nd Lieutenant William A.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] King was escorting the plutonium core of the Fat Man implosion bomb to Tinian, strapped to the floor of one of the 509th's C-54s.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] On 26 July 1945 it made a refueling stop at Hickam Field, Hawaii.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The commander of a combat unit returning to the United States learned that the Skymaster had only one passenger and attempted to enter the C-54 to requisition it as transport for his men.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] He was prevented from doing so by King, who aimed a .45 caliber automatic pistol at the colonel.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 509th transferred four of its 14 training *Silverplate* B-29s to the 216th AAF Base Unit in February 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] In April the third modification increment of *Silverplate*s, which would be their combat aircraft, began coming off the Martin-Omaha assembly line.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] These "fly-away" aircraft were equipped with fuel-injected engines, Curtiss Electric reversible-pitch propellers, pneumatic actuators for rapid opening and closing of bomb bay doors and other improvements.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The remaining 17 *Silverplate* B-29s were placed in storage.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Each bombardier completed at least 50 practice drops of inert pumpkin bombs before Tibbets declared his group combat-ready.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The ground support echelon of the 509th Composite Group, consisting of 44 officers and 815 enlisted men commanded by Major George W.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Westcott of the Headquarters Squadron, received movement orders and moved by rail on 26 April 1945 to its port of embarkation at Seattle, Washington.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] On 6 May the support elements sailed on the *SS Cape Victory* for the Marianas, while group materiel was shipped on the SS *Emile Berliner*.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The *Cape Victory* made brief port calls at Honolulu and Eniwetok but the passengers were not permitted to leave the dock area.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] An advance party of the air echelon, consisting of 29 officers and 61 enlisted men commanded by Group Intelligence Officer (S-2) Lieutenant Colonel Hazen Payette, flew by C-54 to North Field, Tinian, between 15 and 22 May.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It was joined by the ground echelon on 29 May 1945, marking the group's official change of station.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Project Alberta's "Destination Team" also sent most of its members to Tinian to supervise the assembly, loading, and dropping of the bombs under the administrative title of 1st Technical Services Detachment, Miscellaneous War Department Group.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The air echelon consisted of the members of the 393d Bombardment Squadron.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 320th Troop Carrier Squadron remained at Wendover.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It began deploying from Wendover 4 June 1945, with the first B-29 arriving at North Field on 11 June.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Each crew was required to attend the 313th Bombardment Wing's week-long "Lead Crew Ground School" on its arrival.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The ground school indoctrinated combat crews in procedures regarding air-sea rescue, ditching and bailouts, survival, radar bombing, weather, wing and air force regulations, emergency procedures, camera operation, dinghy drills, and other topics related to combat operations.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Two of the group's bombers were not delivered by Martin-Omaha until early July.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] They remained at Wendover until 27 July to act as transports for two of the Fat Man assemblies.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Because of their geographical isolation from the combat crews of other groups, rigidly enforced security measures, and exclusion from participation in regular bombing missions, crews of the 393d Bombardment Squadron were resented and ridiculed as "lacking in discipline" and having a "soft life".
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The Victor (identification assigned by the squadron) numbers previously assigned the 393d aircraft were changed to avoid confusion with B-29s of the groups from whom the tail identifiers were borrowed.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Although all of the B-29s were named as shown, the only nose art applied to the aircraft before the atomic bomb missions was that of *Enola Gay*.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] With the exceptions of Victors 71 and 94, the others were applied some time in August 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] *Luke the Spook* was not named until November 1945, and it is not known if nose art was ever applied to *Jabit III*.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] After ground training for the combat crews, the 509th began operations on 30 June 1945, with a calibration flight involving nine of the B-29s on hand.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] To accustom the Japanese to small groups of American bombers, training flights consisted of three planes that dropped a single bomb before returning to base.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It was hoped that they would be allowed to carry out their job without any Japanese opposition.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] While this training was taking place, the components of the first two atomic bombs were shipped to Tinian by various means.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] For the uranium bomb code-named "Little Boy", fissile components consisted of a cylindrical target and nine washer-like rings that made up the hollow cylinder projectile.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] When the bomb detonated, these would be brought together to create a cylindrical core.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The uranium-235 projectile and bomb pre-assemblies (partly assembled bombs without the fissile components) left Hunters Point Naval Shipyard, California, on 16 July aboard the cruiser USS *Indianapolis*, arriving 26 July.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] L-1, L-2, L-5 and L-6 were expended in test drops.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] L-6 was used in the Iwo Jima dress rehearsal on 29 July.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] This was repeated on 31 July, but this time L-6 was test dropped near Tinian by *Enola Gay*.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] L-11 was the assembly used for the Hiroshima bomb.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] On 26 July three C-54s of the 320th Troop Carrier Squadron left Kirtland Army Air Field, each with three of the uranium-235 target rings, and landed at North Field on 28 July.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The components for the bomb code-named the Fat Man arrived by air the same day.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The bomb's plutonium core (encased in its insertion capsule) and the beryllium-polonium initiator were transported from Kirtland to Tinian by C-54 in the custody of Project Alberta couriers.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Three Fat Man high explosive pre-assemblies designated F31, F32, and F33 were picked up at Kirtland on 28 July by three B-29s, two from the 509th and one from the 216th AAF Base Unit, and transported to North Field, arriving 2 August.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The B-29s were *Luke the Spook* and *Laggin' Dragon* of the 509th, and 42-65386, a phase 3 *Silverplate* of the 216th AAF Base Unit.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] F33 was expended during the final rehearsal on 8 August, and F31 was the bomb dropped on Nagasaki.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] F32 presumably would have been used for a third attack or its rehearsal.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The final item of preparation for the operation came on 29 July 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Orders for the attack were issued to General Carl Spaatz on 25 July under the signature of General Thomas T.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Handy, the acting Chief of Staff of the United States Army, since General of the Army George C.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Marshall was at the Potsdam Conference with the President.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The mission profile for both atomic missions called for weather scouts to precede the strike force by an hour, reporting weather conditions in code over each proposed target.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Each mission had an additional "spare" aircraft pre-positioned on Iwo Jima to take over carrying the bomb if the strike aircraft encountered mechanical problems.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The six combat crews of the Hiroshima mission were briefed on their targets, operational flight data, and the effects of the bomb on 4 August 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Their pre-mission briefing on 5 August, under the terms of Operations Order No.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] 35, covered details on weather and air-sea rescue.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The Order described the bomb to be used as "special".
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Special Mission 13, attacking Hiroshima, was flown as planned and executed without significant problems or diversion from plan.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] *Enola Gay* took off at 02:45, 7.5 long tons (7.6 t) overweight and near maximum gross weight.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Arming of the bomb began eight minutes into the flight and took 25 minutes.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The three target-area aircraft arrived over Iwo Jima approximately three hours into the mission and departed together at 06:07.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The safeties on the bomb were removed at 07:30, 90 minutes before time over target, and 15 minutes later the B-29s began a climb to the 30,000-foot (9,100 m) bombing altitude.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The bomb run began at 09:12, with the drop three minutes later, after which the B-29s immediately performed steep diving turns.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The detonation followed 45.5 seconds after the drop.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Primary and "echo" shock waves overtook the B-29s a minute following the blast, and the smoke cloud was visible to the crews for 90 minutes, by which time they were almost 400 miles (640 km) away.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] *Enola Gay* returned to Tinian at 14:58.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Special Mission 16 was moved up two days from 11 August because of adverse weather forecasts.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Weather also dictated a change in rendezvous to Yakushima, much closer to the target, and an initial cruise altitude of 17,000 feet (5,200 m) instead of 9,300 feet (2,800 m), both of which considerably increased fuel consumption.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Pre-flight inspection discovered an inoperative fuel transfer pump in the 625-US-gallon (2,370 L) aft bomb bay fuel tank, but a decision was made to continue anyway.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The plutonium bomb did not require arming in flight, but did have its safeties removed 30 minutes after the 03:45 takeoff (all times Tinian; Nagasaki times were one hour earlier) when *Bockscar* reached 5,000 feet (1,500 m) of altitude.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] When the daylight rendezvous point was reached at 09:10, the photo plane failed to appear.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The weather planes reported both targets within the required visual attack parameters while *Bockscar* circled Yakushima waiting for the photo plane.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Finally the mission proceeded without the photo plane, thirty minutes behind schedule.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] When *Bockscar* arrived at Kokura 30 minutes later, cloud cover had increased to 70% of the area, and three bomb runs over the next 50 minutes were fruitless in bombing visually.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The commanders decided to reduce power to conserve fuel and divert to Nagasaki, bombing by radar if necessary.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] (two hours behind schedule) using radar; but the Fat Man was dropped visually when a hole opened in the clouds at 12:01.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The photo plane arrived at Nagasaki in time to complete its mission, and the three aircraft diverted to Okinawa, where they arrived at 13:00.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Trying in vain for 20 minutes to contact the control tower at Yontan Airfield to obtain landing clearance, *Bockscar* nearly ran out of fuel.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] While the Nagasaki mission was in progress, two B-29s of the 509th took off from Tinian to return to Wendover.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The crews of Classen in the unnamed Victor 94, and Captain John A.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Wilson in *Jabit III*, together with ground support crews, were sent back to the United States to stage for the possibility of transporting further bomb pre-assemblies to Tinian.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Groves expected to have another atomic bomb ready for shipment on 13 August and use on 19 August, with three more available in September and a further three in October.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Groves ordered that all shipments of material be stopped on 13 August, when the third bomb was still at Site Y.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] After each atomic mission the group conducted other combat operations, making a series of pumpkin bomb attacks on 8 and 14 August.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Six B-29s visually attacked targets at Yokkaichi, Uwajima, Tsuruga, and Tokushima on 8 August, bombing two primary and three secondary targets with five bombs.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Seven aircraft visually attacked Koromo and Nagoya on 14 August.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] *Some Punkins* (Crew B-7, Price) is believed to have dropped the last bombs by the Twentieth Air Force in World War II.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] After the announcement of the Japanese surrender, the 509th Composite Group flew three further training missions involving 31 sorties on 18, 20 and 22 August, then stood down from operations.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The group made a total of 210 operational sorties from 30 June to 22 August, aborted four additional flights, and had only a single aircraft fail to take off.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Altogether, 140 sorties involved the dropping of live ordnance.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Some 60 flights were credited as combat missions: 49 pumpkin bomb and 11 atomic bomb sorties.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Three B-29s (*Full House*, *Straight Flush*, and *Top Secret*) flew six combat missions each.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Crews A-1 (Taylor) and C-11 (Eatherly) flew the most combat missions, six (including one atomic mission) each, while six other crews each flew five.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Only the late arrivals (A-2 [Costello] and C-12 [Zahn]) did not participate in any combat missions, although Costello's B-29 was used by another crew for weather reconnaissance of Nagasaki on the second mission.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Including training and test flights, crews B-8 (McKnight) and C-13 (Bock) flew the most missions, with 20 total (5 combat).
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Crew B-7 (Price) is the only crew to fly all of its missions (18 total, 5 combat) in its normally assigned aircraft, *Some Punkins*.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 509th Composite Group returned to the United States on 6 November 1945, and was stationed at Roswell Army Airfield, New Mexico.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Blanchard replaced Tibbets as group commander on 22 January 1946, and also became the first commander of the 509th Bombardment Wing.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] It was one of the original ten bombardment groups assigned to Strategic Air Command when it was formed on 21 March 1946.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 715th and 830th Bombardment Squadrons were assigned to the 509th on 6 May 1946, and the group was redesignated the 509th Bombardment Group, Very Heavy on 10 July.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 320th Troop Carrier Squadron was inactivated on 19 August.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] At Roswell, the 509th became the nuclear strike and deterrence core of the Strategic Air Command, and was the only unit capable of delivery of nuclear weapons until June 1948, when B-50 Superfortresses were initially deployed.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 509th itself converted to the B-50 in 1950, and transferred its *Silverplate* B-29s to the squadrons of the 97th Bombardment Wing at Biggs Air Force Base, Texas.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] General Groves later saw a *lack of foresight* of himself and others, as sixteen years after in 1961 only four officers were still on active duty; Tibbets plus Ashworthy (a weaponeer) and two bombardiers, Ferebee and Beahan; so few men experienced with atomic weapons were still in the USAF.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The 393d Bombardment Squadron was part of the 504th Bombardment Group (VH) from 12 March to 14 September 1944.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The training and operations of the 509th Composite Group were dramatized in a Hollywood film, *Above and Beyond* (1952), with Robert Taylor cast in the role of Tibbets.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] The story was retold in a partly fictionalized made-for-television film *Enola Gay: The Men, the Mission, the Atomic Bomb* (1980), with Patrick Duffy portraying Tibbets.
[src:arthur-compton/509th-composite-group] Department of the Air Force Special Order GB-294, dated 2 September 1999, awarded the Air Force Outstanding Unit Award (with Valor) to the 509th Composite Group for outstanding achievement in combat for the period 1 July 1945 to 14 August 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Starting from Rainwater's concept of an irregular-shaped liquid drop model of the nucleus, Bohr and Mottelson developed a detailed theory that was in close agreement with experiments.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Since his father, Niels Bohr, had won the prize in 1922, he and his father are one of the several pairs of fathers and sons who have both won the Nobel Prize.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr was born in Copenhagen on 19 June 1922, the fourth of six sons of the physicist Niels Bohr and his wife Margrethe Bohr (née Nørlund).
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] His oldest brother, Christian, died in a boating accident in 1934, and his youngest, Harald, was severely disabled and placed away from the home in Copenhagen at the age of four.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] He would later die from childhood meningitis.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Of the others, Hans became a physician; Erik, a chemical engineer; and Ernest, a lawyer and Olympic athlete who played field hockey for Denmark at the 1948 Summer Olympics in London.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] The family lived at the Institute of Theoretical Physics at the University of Copenhagen, now known as the Niels Bohr Institute, where he grew up surrounded by physicists who were working with his father, such as Hans Kramers, Oskar Klein, Yoshio Nishina, Wolfgang Pauli and Werner Heisenberg.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In 1932, the family moved to the Carlsberg Æresbolig, a mansion donated by Carl Jacobsen, the heir to Carlsberg breweries, to be used as an honorary residence by the Dane who had made the most prominent contribution to science, literature, or the arts.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr went to high school at Sortedam Gymnasium in Copenhagen.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In 1940, shortly after the German occupation of Denmark in April, he entered the University of Copenhagen, where he studied physics.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] He assisted his father, helping draft correspondence and articles related to epistemology and physics.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In September 1943, word reached his family that the Nazis considered them to be Jewish, because Bohr's grandmother, Ellen Adler Bohr, had been Jewish, and that they therefore were in danger of being arrested.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] The Danish resistance helped the family escape by sea to Sweden.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr arrived there in October 1943, and then flew to Britain on a de Havilland Mosquito operated by British Overseas Airways Corporation.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] The Mosquitoes were unarmed high-speed bomber aircraft that had been converted to carry small, valuable cargoes or important passengers.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] By flying at high speed and high altitude, they could cross German-occupied Norway, and yet avoid German fighters.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr, equipped with a parachute, flying suit, and oxygen mask, spent the three-hour flight lying on a mattress in the aircraft's bomb bay.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] On arrival in London, Bohr rejoined his father, who had flown to Britain the week before.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] He officially became a junior researcher at the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research, but actually served as personal assistant and secretary to his father.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] The two worked on Tube Alloys, the British atomic bomb project.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] On 30 December 1943, they made the first of a number of visits to the United States, where his father was a consultant to the Manhattan Project.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Due to his father's fame, they were given false names; Bohr became James Baker, and his father, Nicholas Baker.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In 1945, the director of the Los Alamos Laboratory, J.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Robert Oppenheimer, asked them to review the design of the modulated neutron initiator.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] That they had reached this conclusion put Enrico Fermi's concerns about the viability of the design to rest.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] The initiators performed flawlessly in the bombs used in the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in August 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In August 1945, with the war ended, Bohr returned to Denmark, where he resumed his university education, graduating with a master's degree in 1946, with a thesis concerned with some aspects of atomic stopping power problems.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In early 1948, Bohr became a member of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] While paying a visit to Columbia University, he met Isidor Isaac Rabi, who sparked in him an interest in recent discoveries related to the hyperfine structure of deuterium.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] This led to Bohr becoming a visiting fellow at Columbia from January 1949 to August 1950.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] While in the United States, Bohr married Marietta Soffer on 11 March 1950.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] They had three children: Vilhelm, Tomas and Margrethe.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] By the late 1940s it was known that the properties of atomic nuclei could not be explained by then-current models such as the liquid drop model developed by Niels Bohr amongst others.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] The shell model, developed in 1949 by Maria Goeppert Mayer and others, allowed some additional features to be explained, in particular the so-called magic numbers.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] However, there were also properties that could not be explained, including the non-spherical distribution of charge in certain nuclei.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In a 1950 paper, James Rainwater of Columbia University suggested a variant of the drop model of the nucleus that could explain a non-spherical charge distribution.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Rainwater's model postulated a nucleus like a balloon with balls inside that distort the surface as they move about.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] He discussed the idea with Bohr, who was visiting Columbia at the time, and had independently conceived the same idea, and had, about a month after Rainwater's submission, submitted for publication a paper that discussed the same problem, but along more general lines.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr imagined a rotating, irregular-shaped nucleus with a form of surface tension.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr developed the idea further, in 1951 publishing a paper that comprehensively treated the relationship between oscillations of the surface of the nucleus and the movement of the individual nucleons.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Upon his return to Copenhagen in 1950, Bohr began working with Ben Roy Mottelson to compare the theoretical work with experimental data.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In three papers, that were published in 1952 and 1953, Bohr and Mottelson demonstrated close agreement between theory and experiment; for example, showing that the energy levels of certain nuclei could be described by a rotation spectrum.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] They were thereby able to reconcile the shell model with Rainwater's concept.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] This work stimulated many new theoretical and experimental studies.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr, Mottelson and Rainwater were jointly awarded the 1975 Nobel Prize in Physics "for the discovery of the connection between collective motion and particle motion in atomic nuclei and the development of the theory of the structure of the atomic nucleus based on this connection".
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Because his father had been awarded the prize in 1922, Bohr became one of only four pairs of fathers and sons to win the Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Only after doing his Nobel Prize-winning research did Bohr receive his doctorate from the University of Copenhagen, in 1954, writing his thesis on "Rotational States of Atomic Nuclei".
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr became a professor at the University of Copenhagen in 1956, and, following his father's death in 1962, succeeded him as director of the Niels Bohr Institute, a position he held until 1970.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] He remained active there until he retired in 1992.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] He was also a member of the board of the Nordic Institute for Theoretical Physics from its inception in 1957, and was its director from 1975 to 1981.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In addition to the Nobel Prize, he won the Dannie Heineman Prize for Mathematical Physics in 1960, the Atoms for Peace Award in 1969, H.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] C. Ørsted Medal in 1970, Rutherford Medal and Prize in 1972, John Price Wetherill Medal in 1974, and the Ole Rømer medal in 1976.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr and Mottelson continued to work together, publishing a two-volume monograph, *Nuclear Structure*.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] The first volume, *Single-Particle Motion,* appeared in 1969; the second, *Nuclear Deformations,* in 1975.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In 1972 Bohr was awarded an honorary degree, doctor philos. honoris causa, at the Norwegian Institute of Technology, later part of Norwegian University of Science and Technology.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] He was a member of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters from 1980.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr was also an elected member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, the American Philosophical Society, and the United States National Academy of Sciences.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] In 1981, Bohr became a founding member of the World Cultural Council.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] His son, Tomas Bohr, is a professor of physics at the Technical University of Denmark, working in the area of fluid dynamics.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Aage Bohr died in Copenhagen on 8 September 2009.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] He was survived by his second wife and children.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] Bohr's Nobel Prize medal was sold at auction in November 2011.
[src:arthur-compton/aage-bohr] It was subsequently sold at auction in April 2019 for $90,000.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam was scientific advisor to the Ministry of Science and Technology in Pakistan from 1960 to 1974, a position from which he played a major and influential role in the development of the country's science infrastructure.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam contributed to numerous developments in theoretical and particle physics in Pakistan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He was the founding director of the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission (SUPARCO), and responsible for the establishment of the Theoretical Physics Group (TPG).
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] For this, he is viewed as the "scientific father" of this program.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1974, Abdus Salam departed from his country in protest after the Parliament of Pakistan unanimously passed a parliamentary bill declaring members of the Ahmadiyya Muslim community, to which Salam belonged, non-Muslim.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam's notable achievements include the Pati–Salam model, a Grand Unified Theory he proposed along with Jogesh Pati in 1974, magnetic photon, vector meson, work on supersymmetry and most importantly, electroweak theory, for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam made a major contribution in quantum field theory and in the advancement of Mathematics at Imperial College London.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] With his student, Riazuddin, Salam made important contributions to the modern theory on neutrinos, neutron stars and black holes, as well as the work on modernising quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] As a teacher and science promoter, Salam is remembered as a founder and scientific father of mathematical and theoretical physics in Pakistan during his term as the chief scientific advisor to the president.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam heavily contributed to the rise of Pakistani physics within the global physics community.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Up until shortly before his death, Salam continued to contribute to physics, and to advocate for the development of science in third-world countries.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Abdus Salam was born on 29 January 1926 in Jhang in the Punjab Province of British India (present day in Pakistan) into a Punjabi family professing Ahmadiyya.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He belonged to the Muslim Rajput community, his son Ahmad Salam later recounted that he would tell him stories of Rajput cultural history "of which he was very proud".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Jagjit Singh, in his biography of Salam, says that his family traditionally traced its genealogy back to a Rajput prince named Buddahn who converted to Islam at the hands of a Sufi preacher and later founded the city of Jhang around the year 1160.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam was the son of Chaudhary Muhammad Hussain, a school teacher of Jhang and Hajirah who belonged to Faizullah Chak near Batala.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The name Choudhary Muhammad Hussain gave his son was Abd al-Salam which means "Servant of God".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Abd means servant and Salam is one of the 99 names of God in the Qur'an.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In English, his name is usually transliterated as Abdus Salam, which should be understood as a single given name.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] His father followed the custom of not giving a surname.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Later in his life he added Mohammad to his name.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam established an early reputation in Punjab for outstanding academic performance.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] At age 14, he scored the highest marks ever recorded for the entrance examination of the Punjab University, earning a full scholarship to the Government College of Lahore.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Instead of moving to Lahore immediately, he remained in Jhang and studied for two years at Government Intermediate College.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1942, he passed his FA examinations with the highest scores in the province.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1942, Salam moved to Lahore to study at Government College.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] As a fourth-year student, he published an elegant solution for a mathematical problem originally studied by Srinivasa Ramanujan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1944, his mathematics exam results set a new Punjab record.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam also excelled in Urdu and English literature, which could have led him to pursue further studies in English.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] However, on the recommendation of a mentor, he chose to continue with an M.A. in mathematics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] At his father's urging, Salam attempted to enter the Indian Civil Service (ICS), considered the most prestigious career path for young graduates.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He applied to the Indian Railways but was rejected after failing the medical optical tests; examiners also ruled that he was too young to qualify.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam remained in Lahore, completing his M.A. in mathematics at Government College in 1946 with record marks.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] That same year, he was awarded a scholarship to St John's College, Cambridge, where he enrolled in the undergraduate Mathematical Tripos and graduated in 1949 with a Double First-Class Honours in Mathematics and Physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Although his M.A. from Lahore would have qualified him to proceed directly to research, he still intended at that stage to pursue the ICS, and was advised to obtain a Cambridge mathematics degree first.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1950, he received the Smith's Prize from Cambridge University for the most outstanding pre-doctoral contribution to Physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] After finishing his degrees, Fred Hoyle advised Salam to spend another year in the Cavendish Laboratory to do research in experimental physics, but Salam had no patience for carrying out long experiments in the laboratory.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam returned to Jhang and renewed his scholarship and returned to the United Kingdom to do his doctorate.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] While at Cavendish, Salam entered a Ph.D program.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] His doctoral thesis titled "Developments in quantum theory of fields" contained comprehensive and fundamental work in quantum electrodynamics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] By the time it was published in 1951, it had already gained him an international reputation and the Adams Prize.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] During his doctoral studies, his mentors challenged him to solve within one year an intractable problem which had defied such great minds as Paul Dirac and Richard Feynman.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Within six months, Salam had found a solution for the renormalization of meson theory.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] As he proposed the solution at the Cavendish Laboratory, Salam had attracted the attention of Hans Bethe, J.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] After receiving his doctorate in 1951, Salam returned to Lahore at the Government College University as a professor of mathematics, where he remained till 1954.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1952, he was appointed professor and chair of the Department of Mathematics at the neighbouring University of the Punjab.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In the latter capacity, Salam sought to update the university curriculum, introducing a course in quantum mechanics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He began to supervise the education of students who were particularly influenced by him.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] As a result, Riazuddin remained the only student of Salam who had the privilege to study under Salam at the undergraduate and post-graduate level in Lahore, and post-doctoral level in Cambridge University.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1953, Salam was unable to establish a research institute in Lahore, as he faced strong opposition from his peers.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam went back to Cambridge and joined St John's College.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] During 1957, his tenure at Imperial College, London started.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] As time passed, this department became one of the prestigious research departments that included well known physicists such as Steven Weinberg, Tom Kibble, Gerald Guralnik, C.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] At Cambridge and Imperial College he formed a group of theoretical physicists, the majority of whom were his Pakistani students.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] At age 33, Salam became one of the youngest persons to be elected a Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS) in 1959.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam took a fellowship at the Princeton University in 1959, where he met with J.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Robert Oppenheimer and to whom he presented his research work on neutrinos.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Oppenheimer and Salam discussed the foundation of electrodynamics, problems and their solution.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] His dedicated personal assistant was Jean Bouckley.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1980, Salam became a foreign fellow of the Bangladesh Academy of Sciences.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam made an important and significant contribution in Particle physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In his early career in Pakistan, Salam was greatly interested in mathematical series and their relation to physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam had played an influential role in the advancement of nuclear physics, but he maintained and dedicated himself to mathematics and theoretical physics and focused Pakistan to do more research in theoretical physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] However, he regarded nuclear physics (nuclear fission and nuclear power) as a non-pioneering part of physics as it had already "happened".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Even in Pakistan, Salam was the leading driving force in theoretical physics, with many scientists he continued to influence and encourage to keep their work on theoretical physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam had a prolific research career in theoretical and high-energy physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam had worked on the neutrino with his chiral symmetry.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam later passed his work to Riazuddin, who made pioneering contributions in neutrinos.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam introduced the massive Higgs bosons to the theory of the Standard Model, where he later predicted the existence of proton decay.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1962, Salam published his theoretical work on the vector meson.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1961, Salam began to work with John Clive Ward on symmetries and electroweak unification.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1964, Salam and Ward worked on a Gauge theory for the weak and electromagnetic interaction, subsequently obtaining SU(2) × U(1) model.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam was convinced that all the elementary particle interactions are actually the gauge interactions.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1968, together with Weinberg and Sheldon Glashow, Salam formulated the mathematical concept of their work.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] While in Imperial College, Salam, along with Glashow and Jeffrey Goldstone, mathematically proved the Goldstone's theorem, that a massless spin-zero object must appear in a theory as a result of spontaneous breaking of a continuous global symmetry.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1967-8, Salam and Weinberg incorporated the Higgs mechanism into Glashow's discovery, giving it a modern form in electroweak theory, and thus theorised half of the Standard Model.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1968, together with Weinberg and Sheldon Glashow, Salam finally formulated the mathematical concept of their work.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1966, Salam carried out pioneering work on a hypothetical particle.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam showed the possible electromagnetic interaction between the Magnetic monopole and the C-violation, thus he formulated the magnetic photon.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Following the publication of PRL Symmetry Breaking papers in 1964, Steven Weinberg and Salam were the first to apply the Higgs mechanism to electroweak symmetry breaking.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam provided a mathematical postulation for the interaction between the Higgs boson and the electroweak symmetry theory.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1972, Salam began to work with Indian-American theoretical physicist Jogesh Pati.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Pati wrote to Salam several times expressing interest to work under Salam's direction, in response to which Salam eventually invited Pati to the ICTP seminar in Pakistan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam suggested to Pati that there should be some deep reason why the protons and electrons are so different and yet carry equal but opposite electric charge.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Protons are composed of quarks, but the electroweak theory was concerned only with the electrons and neutrinos, with nothing postulated about quarks.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] If all of nature's ingredients could be brought together in one new symmetry, it might reveal a reason for the various features of these particles and the forces they feel.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] This led to the development of Pati–Salam model in particle physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam had worked on forces from 1959 with Glashow and Weinberg.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Glashow had also formulated the same work, and the theory was combined in 1966.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1967, Salam proved the electroweak unification theory mathematically, and finally published the papers.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] For this achievement, Salam, Glashow, and Weinberg were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1979.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The Nobel Prize Foundation paid tribute to the scientists and issued a statement saying: "For their contributions to the theory of the unified weak and electromagnetic interaction between elementary particles, including, inter alia, the prediction of the weak neutral current".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Only one known official replica of the Nobel Prize Medal was ever produced by the Mint of Pakistan in 1979/80.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] This medal has a large test cut and damage from two to three o'clock.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The replica medal was sold at auction to an unknown bidder on April 23, 2025.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In the 1970s Salam continued trying to unify forces by including the strong interaction in a Grand Unified Theory.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1961 he approached President Khan to set up the country's first national space agency, thus on 16 September 1961 the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission was established, with Salam as its first director.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Before 1960, very little work on scientific development was done, and scientific activities in Pakistan were almost diminished.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam called Ishfaq Ahmad, a nuclear physicist, who had left for Switzerland where he joined CERN, back to Pakistan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] With the support of Salam, PAEC established PAEC Lahore Center-6, with Ishfaq Ahmad as its first director.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1967, Salam became a central and administrative figure to lead the research in Theoretical and Particle physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] With the establishment of the Institute of Physics at Quaid-e-Azam University, research in theoretical and particle physics was engaged.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Under Salam's direction, physicists tackled the greatest outstanding problems in physics and mathematics and their physics research reached a point that prompted worldwide recognition of Pakistani physicists.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] From the 1950s, Salam had tried establishing high-powered research institutes in Pakistan, though he was unable to do so.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He moved PAEC Headquarters to a bigger building, and established research laboratories all over the country.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] On the direction of Salam, Ishrat Hussain Usmani set up plutonium and uranium exploration committees throughout the country.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In October 1961, Salam travelled to the United States and signed a space co-operation agreement between Pakistan and US.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In November 1961, the US National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) started to build a space facility – Flight Test Center (FTC) – at Sonmiani, a coastal town in Balochistan Province.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam served as its first technical director.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] While in the IAEA, Salam had consulted about the establishment of the International Centre for Theoretical Physics (ICTP), a research physics institution, in Trieste, Italy...
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam obtained permission from President Ayub Khan to set up the Karachi Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Also in 1965, led by Salam, the United States and Pakistan signed an agreement in which the US provided Pakistan with a small research reactor (PARR-I).
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam had a long-held dream to establish a research institute in Pakistan, which he had advocated for on many occasions.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1965 again, Salam and architect Edward Durell Stone signed a contract for the establishment of the Pakistan Institute of Nuclear Science and Technology (PINSTECH) at Nilore, Islamabad.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In early 1961, Salam approached President Khan to lay the foundations of Pakistan's first executive agency to co-ordinate space research.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] By executive order on 16 September 1961 the Space and Upper Atmosphere Research Commission (SUPARCO) was established with Salam founding director.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam knew the importance of nuclear technology in Pakistan, for civilian and peaceful purposes.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] But, according to his biographers, Salam played an ambiguous role in Pakistan's own atomic bomb project.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] As late as the 1960s, Salam made an unsuccessful proposal for the establishment of a nuclear fuel reprocessing plant, but it was deferred on economic grounds by Ayub Khan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] According to Rehman, Salam's influence in nuclear development was diminished as late as 1974, and he became critical of Bhutto's control over science.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] But Salam personally did not terminate his connection with the scientists working in the theoretical physics division at PAEC.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] As early as 1972–73, he had been a great advocate for the atomic bomb project, but subsequently took a stance against it after he fell out with Bhutto over the Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan which declared the Ahmaddiya denomination to be non-Islamic.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1965, Salam led the establishing of the nuclear research institute – PINSTECH.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1965, the plutonium Pakistan Atomic Research Reactor (PARR-I) went critical under Salams' leadership.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1973, Salam proposed the idea of establishing an annual college to promote scientific activities in the country to the chairman of PAEC, Munir Khan, who accepted and fully supported the idea.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] This led to the establishment of the International Nathiagali Summer College on Physics and Contemporary Needs (INSC), where each year since 1976 scientists from all over the world come to Pakistan to interact with local scientists.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The first annual INSC conference was held on advanced particle and nuclear physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In November 1971, Salam met with Zulfikar Ali Bhutto in his residence, and following Bhutto's advice, went to the United States to avoid the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam travelled to the US and returned to Pakistan with scientific literature about the Manhattan Project, and calculations involving atomic bombs.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1972, the Government of Pakistan learned about the development status of the first atomic bomb completed under the Indian nuclear programme.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] On 20 January 1972, Salam, as Science Advisor to the president of Pakistan, managed and participated in a secret meeting of nuclear scientists with former prime minister, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in Multan, known as the 'Multan Meeting'.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] At this meeting Bhutto orchestrated the development of a deterrence programme.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Usmani protested, believing that the country had neither the facilities or talent to carry out such an ambitious and technologically demanding project, whilst Salam remained quiet.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Here, Bhutto entrusted Salam and appointed Munir Khan as Chairman of PAEC, and head of the atomic bomb program, as Salam had supported Khan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] A few months after the meeting, Salam, Khan, and Riazuddin, met with Bhutto in his residence where the scientists briefed him about the nuclear weapons program.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] After the meeting, Salam established the 'Theoretical Physics Group' (TPG) in PAEC.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam led groundbreaking work at TPG until 1974.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] An office was set up for Salam in the Prime Ministers' Secretariat by order of Bhutto.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam immediately started to motivate and invite scientists to begin work with PAEC in the development of fission weapons.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In December 1972, two theoretical physicists working at the International Centre for Theoretical Physics were asked by Salam to report to Munir Ahmad Khan, the scientific director of the program.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] This marked the beginning of the TPG, reporting directly to Salam.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The TPG, in PAEC, was assigned to conduct research in fast neutron calculations, hydrodynamics (how the explosion produced by a chain reaction might behave), problems of neutron diffusion, and the development of theoretical designs of Pakistan's nuclear weapon devices.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Later, the TPG under Riazuddin began to directly report to Salam, and the work on the theoretical design of the nuclear weapon was completed in 1977.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1972, Salam formed the Mathematical Physics Group, under Raziuddin Siddiqui, that was charged, with TPG, with carrying out research in the theory of simultaneity during the detonation process, and the mathematics involved in the theory of nuclear fission.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Following India's surprise nuclear test – Pokhran-I – in 1974, Munir Ahmad Khan had called a meeting to initiate work on an atomic bomb.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam was there and Muhammad Hafeez Qureshi was appointed head of the Directorate of Technical Development (DTD) in PAEC.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The DTD was set up to co-ordinate the work of the various specialised groups of scientists and engineers working on different aspects of the atomic bomb.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The word "bomb" was never used in this meeting, but the participants fully understood what was being discussed.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In March 1974, Salam and Khan also established the Wah Group Scientist that was charged with manufacturing materials, explosive lenses and triggering mechanism development of the weapon.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Following the setting up of DTD, Salam, Riazuddin and Munir Ahmad Khan, visited the Pakistan Ordnance Factories (POF) where they held talks with senior military engineers led by POF chairman Lieutenant-General Qamar Ali Mirza.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] It was there that the Corps of Engineers built the Metallurgical Laboratory in Wah Cantonment in 1976.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam remained associated with the nuclear weapons programme until mid-1974, when he left the country after Ahmadi were declared non-Muslims by the Pakistani Parliament.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] His own relations with Prime minister Bhutto fell out and turned into open hostility after the Ahmadiyya Community was declared as not-Islamic; he lodged a public and powerful protest against Bhutto regarding this issue and gave great criticism to Bhutto over his control over science.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In spite of this, Salam maintained close relations with the theoretical physics division at PAEC who kept him informed about the status of the calculations needed to calculate the performance of the atomic bomb, according to Norman Dombey.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In the 1980s, Salam personally approved many appointments and a large influx of Pakistani scientists to the associateship program at ICTP and CERN, and engaged in research in theoretical physics with his students at the ICTP.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1964, Salam founded the International Centre for Theoretical Physics (ICTP), Trieste, in Italy and served as its director until 1993.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1974, he founded the International Nathiagali Summer College (INSC) to promote science in Pakistan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The INSC is an annual meeting of scientists from all over the world who come to Pakistan and hold discussions on physics and science.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Even today, the INSC holds annual meetings, and Salam's pupil Riazuddin has been its director since its start.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1997, the scientists at ICTP commemorated Salam and renamed ICTP as the "Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Throughout the years, he served on a number of United Nations committees concerning science and technology in developing countries.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam also founded the Third World Academy of Sciences (TWAS) and was a leading figure in the creation of a number of international centres dedicated to the advancement of science and technology.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1979, Salam said: *Physicists believed there are four fundamental forces of nature; the gravitational force, the weak and strong nuclear force, and the electromagnetic force*.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1981, Salam became a founding member of the World Cultural Council.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Although Salam left Pakistan, he did not terminate his connection to home.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He continued inviting Pakistan's scientists to ICTP, and maintained a research programme for them.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Abdus Salam was a very private individual, who kept his public and personal lives quite separate.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He married twice; first time to a cousin, the second time as well in accordance with Islamic law.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] At his death, he was survived by three daughters and a son by his first wife, and a son and daughter by his second, Professor Dame Louise Johnson, formerly Professor of molecular biophysics at Oxford University.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Two of his daughters are Anisa Bushra Salam Bajwa and Aziza Rahman.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam was an Ahmadi Muslim, who saw his religion as a fundamental part of his scientific work.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1974, the Pakistan parliament made the Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan that declared Ahmadis to be non-Muslim.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In protest, Salam left Pakistan for London.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] After his departure, he did not completely cut his ties to Pakistan, and kept a close association with the Theoretical Physics Group as well as academic scientists from the Pakistan Atomic Energy Commission.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Abdus Salam died on 21 November 1996 at the age of 70 in Oxford, England, from progressive supranuclear palsy.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] His body was returned to Pakistan and kept in Darul Ziafat, where some 13,000 men and women visited to pay their last respects.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Approximately 30,000 people attended his funeral prayers.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam was buried in Bahishti Maqbara, a cemetery established by the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community at Rabwah, Punjab, Pakistan, next to his parents' graves.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The epitaph on his tomb initially read "First Muslim Nobel Laureate".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The Pakistani government removed "Muslim" and left only his name on the headstone.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] It is the only nation to officially declare that Ahmadis are non-Muslim.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The word "Muslim" was initially obscured on the orders of a local magistrate before moving to the national level.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Under Ordinance XX of 1984, being an Ahmadi, he was considered a non-Muslim according to the definition provided in the Second Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam's work in Pakistan has been far reaching and regarded as highly influential.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He is remembered by his peers and students as the "father of Pakistan's school of Theoretical Physics" as well as Pakistan's science.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam was a charismatic and iconic figure, a symbol among them of what they were working or researching toward in their fields.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] His students, fellow scientists and engineers, remembered him as brilliant teacher, and engaging researcher who would also influence others to do the same.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The International Centre for Theoretical Physics established by Salam has continued to train scientists from developing countries.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam founded the Space Research Commission of and was its first director.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1998, the Government of Pakistan issued a commemorative stamp to honour Salam as part of its "Scientists of Pakistan" series.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] His alma mater, Government College Lahore, now a university, has the *Abdus Salam Chair in Physics* and Abdus Salam School of Mathematical Sciences named after him.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] *The Abdus Salam Chair* was also established in his honour at the Syed Babar Ali School of Science and Engineering in the Lahore University of Management Sciences.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] He made a significant contribution towards the 2012 success in the search for the Higgs boson.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In August 1996 another lifelong friend, Munir Ahmad Khan, met Salam in Oxford.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] A 1997 quote by Khan was "[We] Pakistanis may choose to ignore Dr.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] However, Salam's legacy is often ignored in the Pakistani education system despite his achievements.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] According to the documentary 'Salam: The First ****** Nobel Laureate,' very few young Pakistanis have heard of him, and his name is not mentioned in Pakistani school textbooks.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 2020, a group of students belonging to the State Youth Parliament desecrated an image of Salam that was present at a college in Gujranwala, while chanting slogans against the Ahmadiyya Muslim community.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] This deliberate effort to stifle mention of Salam is attributed to Salam belonging to the Ahmadiyya Muslim community, who have faced state-sponsored discrimination since the 1970s.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] LLC started formally researching and developing a film on the science and life of Abdus Salam in 2004, two years after the producers had conceived of the idea.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] A fundraising teaser was released by Kailoola Productions to coincide with Salam's birth anniversary on 29 January 2017.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The post-production phase of this documentary film, pending funding, is estimated at US$150,000.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The film *Salam: The First ****** Nobel Laureate*, directed by the Indian-American documentary filmmaker Anand Kamalakar, was announced in 2018 and released on Netflix in October 2019.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Pilgrim Films released *The Dream of Symmetry* in September 2011.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Their press release describes it as presenting "the extraordinary figure of Abdus Salam, who not only was an outstanding scientist but also a generous humanitarian and a valuable person.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1971, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1979, and the American Philosophical Society in 1992.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1997, scientists at ICTP renamed the institute as the Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics in the honour of Salam.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam's services have been recognised in Pakistan, as his students have openly spoken and stressed the importance of Science and Technology in Pakistan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1999, per the recommendation of Ishfaq Ahmad, the Government of Pakistan led the establishment of the Abdus Salam Chair in Physics at the Government College University.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] On 22 November 2009, the director of the Abdus Salam International Centre for Theoretical Physics gifted the original Nobel Prize Certificate to his alma mater.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 2011, GCU's Salam Chair in Physics held a one-day-long conference that was attributed to Abdus Salam.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam's students Ghulam Murtaza, Pervez Hoodbhoy, Riazuddin and Tariq Zaidi discussed the life and works of Salam, and brought to light his achievements in Pakistan and Physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] While covering the media converge on Salam's tribute, *The News International*, referred to Salam as the "great Pakistan scientist".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Bouchet-ICTP Institute was renamed as the Edward Bouchet Abdus Salam Institute.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 2003, the Government of Punjab created an institute of excellence for the Mathematical Sciences, the Abdus Salam School of Mathematical Sciences, in Salam's Alma mater – Government College University.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 2008, in an opinion piece, *Daily Times* called Salam "one of the greatest scientists Pakistan has ever produced".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 2015, the Academy of Young Researchers and Scholars, Lahore, renamed its library as the "Abdus Salam Library".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In the town of Vaughan, Ontario, Canada, near the headquarters of the Canadian branch of the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community, of which Abdus Salam was a member, the community has named a street after him, 'Abdus Salam Street', while at CERN in Geneva, Switzerland there is 'Route Salam'.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Additionally, there are two annual Abdus Salam science fairs, one held in Canada and the other in the US.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Each is organised as a National event for young scientists from the Ahmadiyya Muslim Community in an effort to motivate youth toward scientific endeavour.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] On 6 December 2016, Pakistan's prime minister Nawaz Sharif approved the renaming of Quaid-i-Azam University's (QAU) physics centre to the Professor Abdus Salam Center for Physics.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] It was also announced that the *Professor Abdus Salam Fellowship* will be established, which will include five annual fully funded Pakistani PhD students in the field of Physics in "leading international universities".
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In November 2020, English Heritage erected a blue plaque in Salam's honour in Campion Road, Putney, London, at the house that was his London home for almost 40 years.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In June 2023, Imperial College, London announced the renaming of its Imperial College Central Library as the Abdus Salam Library.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1979, Salam was awarded a third of the 1979 Nobel Prize in Physics, along with Glashow and Weinberg, *For their contributions to the theory of the unified weak and electromagnetic interaction between elementary particles, including, inter alia, the prediction of the weak neutral current*.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam received high civil and science awards from all over the world.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam is recipient of first high civil awards – Star of Pakistan.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Below is the list of awards that were conferred to Salam in his lifetime.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The Abdus Salam Award (also called the Salam Prize) is an award established to recognise high achievements and contributions in physical and natural sciences.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] In 1979, Riazuddin, Fayyazuddin and Asghar Qadir met with Salam, and presented the idea of creating an award to appreciate scientists, resident in Pakistan, in their respective fields.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam donated the money he had won as he felt that he had no right use for the prize money.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] It was endowed by Asghar Qadir, Riazuddin and Fayyazuddin in 1980, and it was first awarded in 1981.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The winners are selected by a committee (consisted of Aghar Qadir, Fayyazuddin, Riazuddin, and others) of the Center for Advanced Mathematics and Physics (CAMP), which administers the award.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The Abdus Salam Medal is presented by the Third World Academy of Sciences in Trieste, Italy.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] First given in 1995, the award is presented to the people who have served the cause of science in the Developing World.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] The Abdus Salam Shield of Honor in Mathematics was initiated by the National Mathematical Society of Pakistan to promote and recognize quality research in Mathematics in 2015.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] It was awarded for the first time in 2016.
[src:arthur-compton/abdus-salam] Salam's primary focus was research on the physics of elementary particles.
[src:arthur-compton/abram-litton] Abram Litton was born in Dublin on May 20, 1814.
[src:arthur-compton/abram-litton] His family emigrated from Ireland to Nashville, Tennessee when he was three years old.
[src:arthur-compton/abram-litton] He graduated from the University of Nashville at age 17.
[src:arthur-compton/abram-litton] In 1839, he moved to Europe to study chemistry.
[src:arthur-compton/abram-litton] Three years later, he returned to the United States to accept the Professorship of Chemistry at Washington University in St.
[src:arthur-compton/abram-litton] In 1843, he became professor of chemistry in the St.
[src:arthur-compton/abram-litton] Louis Medical College (Washington University School of Medicine**)**.
[src:arthur-compton/abram-litton] He held that position for fifty years, and died in St.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] In physics, **absorption** of electromagnetic radiation is how matter (typically electrons bound in atoms) takes up a photon's energy—and so transforms electromagnetic energy into internal energy of the absorber (for example, thermal energy).
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] A notable effect of the absorption of electromagnetic radiation is attenuation of the radiation; attenuation is the gradual reduction of the intensity of light waves as they propagate through a medium.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Although the absorption of waves does not usually depend on their intensity (linear absorption), in certain conditions (optics) the medium's transparency changes by a factor that varies as a function of wave intensity, and saturable absorption (or nonlinear absorption) occurs.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Many approaches can potentially quantify radiation absorption, with key examples following.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] All these quantities measure, at least to some extent, how well a medium absorbs radiation.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Which among them practitioners use varies by field and technique, often due simply to the convention.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] The absorbance of an object quantifies how much of the incident light is absorbed by it (instead of being reflected or refracted).
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] This may be related to other properties of the object through the Beer–Lambert law.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Precise measurements of the absorbance at many wavelengths allow the identification of a substance via absorption spectroscopy, where a sample is illuminated from one side, and the intensity of the light that exits from the sample in every direction is measured.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] A few examples of absorption are ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy, infrared spectroscopy, and X-ray absorption spectroscopy.
[src:arthur-compton/absorption-electromagnetic-radiation] Understanding and measuring the absorption of electromagnetic radiation has a variety of applications.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1919, Compton was awarded one of the first two National Research Council Fellowships that allowed students to study abroad.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He chose to go to the University of Cambridge's Cavendish Laboratory in England, where he studied the scattering and absorption of gamma rays.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Further research along these lines led to the discovery of the Compton effect.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton used X-rays to investigate ferromagnetism, concluding that it was a result of the alignment of electron spins, and studied cosmic rays, discovering that they were made principally of positively charged particles.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] During World War II, Compton was a key figure in the Manhattan Project that developed the first nuclear weapons.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] His reports were important in launching the project.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton oversaw Enrico Fermi's creation of Chicago Pile-1, the first nuclear reactor, which went critical on December 2, 1942.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The Metallurgical Laboratory was also responsible for the design and operation of the X-10 Graphite Reactor at Oak Ridge, Tennessee.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Plutonium began being produced in the Hanford Site reactors in 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] After the War, Compton became Chancellor of Washington University in St.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] During his tenure, the university formally desegregated its undergraduate divisions, named its first female full professor, and enrolled a record number of students after wartime veterans returned to the United States.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Arthur Holly Compton was born on September 10, 1892, in Wooster, Ohio, the son of Elias Compton and Otelia Catherine Augspurger, who was named American Mother of the Year in 1939 and was of German Mennonite descent.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Elias was Dean of the University of Wooster (now the College of Wooster), which Arthur also attended.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Arthur's eldest brother, Karl, who also attended Wooster, earned a Ph.D. in physics from Princeton University in 1912, and was President of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology from 1930 to 1948.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] His second brother, Wilson, likewise attended Wooster, earned his Ph.D. in economics from Princeton in 1916 and was President of the State College of Washington (now Washington State University) from 1944 to 1951.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] All three brothers were members of the Alpha Tau Omega fraternity.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton was initially interested in astronomy, and took a photograph of Halley's Comet in 1910.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Around 1913, he described an experiment where an examination of the motion of water in a circular tube demonstrated the rotation of the earth, a device now known as the Compton generator.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] That year, he graduated from Wooster with a B.S. and entered Princeton, where he received his M.A. in 1914.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton then studied for his Ph.D. in physics under the supervision of Hereward Lester Cooke, writing his thesis titled *The Intensity of X-Ray Reflection, and the Distribution of the Electrons in Atoms*.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] When Arthur Compton earned his Ph.D. in 1916, he, Karl, and Wilson became the first group of three brothers to earn PhDs from Princeton.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Later, they would become the first such trio to simultaneously head American colleges.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Their sister, Mary, married a missionary, C.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Herbert Rice, who became the Principal of Forman Christian College in Lahore.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In June 1916, Compton married Betty Charity McCloskey, a Wooster classmate and fellow graduate.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] They had two sons, Arthur Alan Compton and John Joseph Compton.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1916, Compton became a physics instructor at the University of Minnesota.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1917, he became a research engineer at the Westinghouse Lamp Company in Pittsburgh, where he worked on the development of the sodium-vapor lamp.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] During World War I, he developed aircraft instrumentation for the Signal Corps.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He chose to go to the University of Cambridge's Cavendish Laboratory in England.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Working with George Paget Thomson, the son of J.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Thomson, Compton studied the scattering and absorption of gamma rays.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He observed that the scattered rays were more easily absorbed than the original source.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton was greatly impressed by the Cavendish scientists—especially Ernest Rutherford, Charles Galton Darwin, and Arthur Eddington—and he ultimately named his second son after J.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] From 1926 to 1927, Compton taught at the Department of Chemistry of the University of the Punjab where he was a Guggenheim Fellow.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] For a time, Compton was a deacon at a Baptist church.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Returning to the United States, Compton was appointed Wayman Crow Professor of Physics, and head of the Department of Physics at Washington University in St.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1922, he found that X-ray quanta scattered by free electrons had longer wavelengths and, in accordance with Planck's relation, less energy than the incoming X-rays, the surplus energy having been transferred to the electrons.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] This discovery, known as the "Compton effect" or "Compton scattering", demonstrated the particle concept of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1923, Compton published a paper in the *Physical Review* that explained the X-ray shift by attributing particle-like momentum to photons, something Einstein had invoked for his 1905 Nobel Prize-winning explanation of the photoelectric effect.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] First postulated by Max Planck in 1900, these were conceptualized as elements of light "quantized" by containing a specific amount of energy depending only on the frequency of the light.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In his paper, Compton derived the mathematical relationship between the shift in wavelength and the scattering angle of the X-rays by assuming that each scattered X-ray photon interacted with only one electron.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The quantity *h*⁄*mec* is known as the Compton wavelength of the electron; it is equal to 2.43×10−12 m.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The wavelength shift *λ′* − *λ* lies between zero (for *θ* = 0°) and twice the Compton wavelength of the electron (for *θ* = 180°).
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He found that some X-rays experienced no wavelength shift despite being scattered through large angles; in each of these cases the photon failed to eject an electron.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Thus the magnitude of the shift is related not to the Compton wavelength of the electron, but to the Compton wavelength of the entire atom, which can be upwards of 10,000 times smaller.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] It was particularly telling that diffraction in a crystal lattice could only be explained with reference to its wave nature.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] It earned Compton the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1927.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Simon developed the method for observing at the same instant individual scattered X-ray photons and the recoil electrons.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In Germany, Walther Bothe and Hans Geiger independently developed a similar method.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1923, Compton moved to the University of Chicago as Professor of Physics, a position he would occupy for the next 22 years.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1925, he demonstrated that the scattering of 130,000-volt X-rays from the first sixteen elements in the periodic table (hydrogen through sulfur) were polarized, a result predicted by J.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] William Duane from Harvard University spearheaded an effort to prove that Compton's interpretation of the Compton effect was wrong.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Duane carried out a series of experiments to disprove Compton, but instead found evidence that Compton was correct.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1924, Duane conceded that this was the case.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton investigated the effect of X-rays on the sodium and chlorine nuclei in salt.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He used X-rays to investigate ferromagnetism, concluding that it was a result of the alignment of electron spins.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1926, he became a consultant for the Lamp Department at General Electric.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1934, he returned to England as Eastman visiting professor at Oxford University.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] While there, General Electric asked him to report on activities at General Electric Company plc's research laboratory at Wembley.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton was intrigued by the possibilities of the research there into fluorescent lamps.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] His report prompted a research program in America that developed it.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton's first book, *X-Rays and Electrons*, was published in 1926.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In it he showed how to calculate the densities of diffracting materials from their X-ray diffraction patterns.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He revised his book with the help of Samuel K.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Allison to produce *X-Rays in Theory and Experiment* (1935).
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] This work remained a standard reference for the next three decades.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] By the early 1930s, Compton had become interested in cosmic rays.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] At the time, their existence was known but their origin and nature remained speculative.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Their presence could be detected using a spherical "bomb" containing compressed air or argon gas and measuring its electrical conductivity.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Trips to Europe, India, Mexico, Peru and Australia gave Compton the opportunity to measure cosmic rays at different altitudes and latitudes.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Along with other groups who made observations around the globe, they found that cosmic rays were 15% more intense at the poles than at the equator.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In September 1932, Compton attributed this to the effect of cosmic rays being made principally of charged particles, rather than photons as Robert Millikan had suggested, with the latitude effect being due to Earth's magnetic field.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] This resulted in a public altercation between Millikan and Compton in December.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In April 1941, Vannevar Bush, head of the wartime National Defense Research Committee (NDRC), created a special committee headed by Compton to report on the NDRC uranium program.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton's report, which was submitted in May 1941, foresaw the prospects of developing radiological weapons, nuclear propulsion for ships, and nuclear weapons using uranium-235 or the recently discovered plutonium.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In October he wrote another report on the practicality of an atomic bomb.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] For this report, he worked with Enrico Fermi on calculations of the critical mass of uranium-235, conservatively estimating it to be between 20 kilograms (44 lb) and 2 tonnes (2.0 long tons; 2.2 short tons).
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He also discussed the prospects for uranium enrichment with Harold Urey, spoke with Eugene Wigner about how plutonium might be produced in a nuclear reactor, and with Robert Serber about how the plutonium produced in a reactor might be separated from uranium.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] His report, submitted in November, stated that a bomb was feasible, although he was more conservative about its destructive power than Mark Oliphant and his British colleagues.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The final draft of Compton's November report made no mention of using plutonium, but after discussing the latest research with Ernest Lawrence, Compton became convinced that a plutonium bomb was also feasible.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In December, Compton was placed in charge of the plutonium project.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He hoped to achieve a controlled chain reaction by January 1943, and to have a bomb by January 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] To tackle the problem, he had the research groups working on plutonium and nuclear reactor design at Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of California, Berkeley, concentrated together as the Metallurgical Laboratory in Chicago.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Its objectives were to produce reactors to convert uranium to plutonium, to find ways to chemically separate the plutonium from the uranium, and to design and build an atomic bomb.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In June 1942, the United States Army Corps of Engineers assumed control of the nuclear weapons program and Compton's Metallurgical Laboratory became part of the Manhattan Project.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] That month, Compton gave Robert Oppenheimer responsibility for bomb design.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] It fell to Compton to decide which of the different types of reactor designs that the Metallurgical Laboratory scientists had devised should be pursued, even though a successful reactor had not yet been built.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] When labor disputes delayed construction of the Metallurgical Laboratory's new home in the Argonne Forest preserve, Compton decided to build Chicago Pile-1, the first nuclear reactor, under the stands at Stagg Field.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Under Fermi's direction, it went critical on December 2, 1942.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton arranged for Mallinckrodt to undertake the purification of uranium ore, and with DuPont to build the plutonium semi-works at Oak Ridge, Tennessee.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] A major crisis for the plutonium program occurred in July 1943, when Emilio Segrè's group confirmed that plutonium created in the X-10 Graphite Reactor at Oak Ridge contained high levels of plutonium-240.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Its spontaneous fission ruled out the use of plutonium in a gun-type nuclear weapon.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Oppenheimer's Los Alamos Laboratory met the challenge by designing and building an implosion-type nuclear weapon.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton was at the Hanford site in September 1944 to watch the first reactor being brought online.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The first batch of uranium slugs was fed into Reactor B at Hanford in November 1944, and shipments of plutonium to Los Alamos began in February 1945.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Throughout the war, Compton would remain a prominent scientific adviser and administrator.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1945, he served, along with Lawrence, Oppenheimer, and Fermi, on the Scientific Panel that recommended military use of the atomic bomb against Japan.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He was awarded the Medal for Merit for his services to the Manhattan Project.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] After the war ended, Compton resigned his chair as Charles H.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Swift Distinguished Service Professor of Physics at the University of Chicago and returned to Washington University in St.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Louis, where he was inaugurated as the university's ninth chancellor in 1946.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] During Compton's time as chancellor, the university formally desegregated its undergraduate divisions in 1952, named its first female full professor, and enrolled record numbers of students as wartime veterans returned to the United States.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] His reputation and connections in national scientific circles allowed him to recruit many nationally renowned scientific researchers to the university.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Despite Compton's accomplishments, he was criticized then, and subsequently by historians, for moving too slowly toward full racial integration, making Washington University the last major institution of higher learning in St.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Louis to open its doors to African Americans.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] During the period, in 1953, he is credited with the prototyping of the "traffic control bump", the predecessor of the speed bump, in order to slow down traffic near the university and make roads overall safer by slowing down vehicles.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton retired as chancellor in 1954, but remained on the faculty as Distinguished Service Professor of Natural Philosophy until his retirement from the full-time faculty in 1961.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In retirement he wrote *Atomic Quest*, a personal account of his role in the Manhattan Project, which was published in 1956.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton died of a cerebral hemorrhage on March 15, 1962, in Berkeley, California, at the age of 69.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He was outlived by his wife (who died in 1980) and sons.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton is buried in the Wooster Cemetery in Wooster, Ohio.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Before his death, he was professor-at-large at the University of California, Berkeley for spring 1962.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton was one of a handful of scientists and philosophers to propose a two-stage model of free will.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Others include William James, Henri Poincaré, Karl Popper, Henry Margenau, and Daniel Dennett.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In 1931, Compton championed the idea of human freedom based on quantum indeterminacy, and invented the notion of amplification of microscopic quantum events to bring chance into the macroscopic world.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In his somewhat bizarre mechanism, he imagined sticks of dynamite attached to his amplifier, anticipating the Schrödinger's cat paradox, which was published in 1935.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Reacting to criticisms that his ideas made chance the direct cause of people's actions, Compton clarified the two-stage nature of his idea in an *Atlantic Monthly* article in 1955.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] First there is a range of random possible events, then one adds a determining factor in the act of choice.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] His father Elias was an ordained Presbyterian minister.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton lectured on a "Man's Place in God's World" at Yale University, Western Theological Seminary and the University of Michigan in 1934–35.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The lectures formed the basis of his book *The Freedom of Man*.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] His chapter "Death, or Life Eternal?" argued for Christian immortality and quoted verses from the Bible.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] From 1948 to 1962, Compton was an elder of the Second Presbyterian Church in St.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] In his later years, he co-authored the book *Man's Destiny in Eternity*.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton set Jesus as the center of his faith in God's eternal plan.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] He once commented that he could see Jesus' spirit at work in the world as an aspect of God alive in men and women.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton crater on the Moon is co-named for Compton and his brother, Karl.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The physics research building at Washington University in St Louis is named in his honor, as is the university's top fellowship for undergraduate students studying math, physics, or planetary science.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] Compton invented a more gentle, elongated, and ramped version of the speed bump called the "Holly hump", many of which were installed on the roads of the Washington University campus.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The University of Chicago remembered Compton and his achievements by dedicating the Arthur H.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] It is now listed as a National Historic Landmark.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] NASA's Compton Gamma Ray Observatory was named in honor of Compton.
[src:arthur-compton/arthur-compton] The Compton effect is central to the gamma ray detection instruments aboard the observatory.
